\section{Automobile Industry: Supply Chain Responses under Tariff Shock}

\subsection{Current Position of Japanese Automobiles in the U.S. Market}
The U.S. is the largest export destination for Japanese vehicles. Currently, the supply chain operates on a hybrid model: direct exports from Japan (high quality, tariff-sensitive) and localized production in North America (cost-efficient, tariff-exempt under USMCA). However, the proposed reciprocal tariffs threaten to disrupt this equilibrium, forcing manufacturers to re-evaluate their production facility locations.

\subsection{Model: Non-Tariff Response Strategies}
To simulate the strategic behavior of Japanese automakers, we establish a \textbf{Cost Minimization Model}. The objective is to select the production location $L \in \{\text{Japan}, \text{Mexico}, \text{USA}\}$ that minimizes the total unit cost $TC$:

\begin{equation}
    \min_{L} TC_L = C_{prod}^L + C_{logistics}^L + \mathbb{I}(L=\text{Japan}) \cdot (P \times \tau)
\end{equation}

Where $C_{prod}$ denotes production costs (influenced by labor rates), $C_{logistics}$ represents shipping fees, $P$ is the vehicle value, $\tau$ is the variable tariff rate, and $\mathbb{I}$ is an indicator function.

