The Sankey diagrams demonstrate a clear \textbf{Trade Diversion Effect}:
\begin{enumerate}
    \item \textbf{Direct Export Compression}: The direct flow from Japanese factories to the U.S. market narrows significantly under high tariffs.
    \item \textbf{Indirect Routing}: Flows via Mexican factories increase, utilizing Mexico as a manufacturing hub to bypass high direct tariffs.
    \item \textbf{Reshoring to U.S.}: Investment in U.S. local factories expands, validating the effectiveness of tariffs in driving partial manufacturing reshoring (FDI).
\end{enumerate}

\subsection{Impact on U.S. Industry}
The strategic shift entails dual impacts on the U.S. economy:
\begin{itemize}
    \item \textbf{Positive Impact on Employment}: The expansion of U.S. local factories (as shown in the green flow in Figure \ref{fig:sankey}) directly increases demand for domestic manufacturing labor.
    \item \textbf{Negative Impact on Consumer Prices}: Although local production avoids tariffs, the baseline production cost in the U.S. ($C_{prod}^{USA}$) is higher than in Japan or Mexico due to labor costs. This cost premium will likely be passed on to U.S. consumers, leading to higher vehicle prices.
\end{itemize}